	Great — let’s draw the **exact JVM memory diagram** for all 3 cases so you can *visualize it like an interviewer expects* 🔥

	---

	# 🧠 JVM Memory Areas (Quick Recall)

	```
	Method Area  → Class metadata, methods, static data
	Heap         → Objects
	Stack        → Method calls, local variables
	```

	---

	# 🔥 CASE 1: Anonymous Class as INSTANCE FIELD

	### Code

	```java
	class Outer {
	    Interface tea = new Interface() {
	        public void prepare() {
	            System.out.println("Tea");
	        }
	    };
	}
	```

	---

	## 🧾 Memory Diagram

	```
	STEP 1: Class Loading
	---------------------
	Method Area:
	  Outer.class
	  Outer$1.class   (anonymous class)

	------------------------------------------------

	STEP 2: Object Creation → new Outer()

	Heap:
	  [Outer Object]
	      tea → null   (default value)

	------------------------------------------------

	STEP 3: Instance Initialization (IMPORTANT)
	------------------------------------------
	Heap:
	  [Outer Object]
	      tea → [Anonymous Object (Outer$1)]

	  [Anonymous Object]
	      prepare() method

	------------------------------------------------

	STEP 4: Constructor Executes
	(no change to tea unless modified)
	```

	---

	## 🔥 KEY POINT

	> Anonymous object is created **BEFORE constructor body executes**

	---

	# 🔥 CASE 2: Anonymous Class INSIDE NON-STATIC METHOD

	### Code

	```java
	public Interface getTea() {
	    return new Interface() {
	        public void prepare() {
	            System.out.println("Tea");
	        }
	    };
	}
	```

	---

	## 🧾 Memory Diagram

	```
	STEP 1: Class Loading
	---------------------
	Method Area:
	  Outer.class
	  Outer$1.class

	------------------------------------------------

	STEP 2: new Outer()

	Heap:
	  [Outer Object]

	------------------------------------------------

	STEP 3: Method Call → obj.getTea()

	Stack:
	  getTea() frame created

	Heap:
	  [Anonymous Object (Outer$1)]

	------------------------------------------------

	STEP 4: Method Returns

	Stack:
	  frame removed

	Heap:
	  Anonymous object still exists IF reference is returned

	If NOT stored:
	  → Eligible for GC
	```

	---

	## 🔥 KEY POINT

	> Object created **only when method executes**

	---

	# 🔥 CASE 3: STATIC METHOD

	### Code

	```java
	public static Interface getTea() {
	    return new Interface() {
	        public void prepare() {
	            System.out.println("Tea");
	        }
	    };
	}
	```

	---

	## 🧾 Memory Diagram

	```
	STEP 1: Class Loading
	---------------------
	Method Area:
	  Outer.class
	  Outer$1.class
	  getTea() [static method]

	------------------------------------------------

	STEP 2: Call → Outer.getTea()

	Stack:
	  getTea() frame

	Heap:
	  [Anonymous Object (Outer$1)]

	------------------------------------------------

	STEP 3: Return

	Heap:
	  Object remains IF referenced
	  Otherwise → Eligible for GC
	```

	---

	## 🔥 KEY POINT

	> No Outer object created
	> Only anonymous object in heap
	> Use When No Need to access the Outer Class Instance Fields and Methods
	> + point if above ccondition is satisfied is >>> Saves Memory , Increase Efficiency

	---

	# 🚀 FINAL COMPARISON DIAGRAM

	```
	                METHOD AREA
	        ---------------------------
	        Outer.class
	        Outer$1.class
	        (getTea() if static)

	                ↓

	CASE 1 (Field)
	Heap:
	 [Outer Object]
	     ↓
	 [Anonymous Object]

	----------------------------------

	CASE 2 (Non-static method)
	Stack → Method call
	Heap  → Anonymous object (on demand)

	----------------------------------

	CASE 3 (Static method)
	Stack → Static call
	Heap  → Anonymous object (on demand)
	```

	---

	# 🎯 FINAL INTERVIEW LINE

	> Anonymous inner classes are compiled into separate class files (Outer$1) and loaded into the method area. Their objects are always created in heap memory, either during instance initialization (if used as a field) or during method execution (if used inside a method), regardless of whether the method is static or non-static.

